            <section id="project-summary">
                <h2>Project Summary</h2>
                <p>Recessions have been a recurring part of U.S. economic history—from the 1973–1975 energy crisis to
                    the 2007–2009 housing collapse and the 2020 COVID-19 downturn. These events have wide-reaching
                    impacts on employment, housing affordability, financial markets, and overall economic stability.
                    Despite their significance, recessions are often only recognized after substantial damage has
                    already occurred.</p>
                <p>This project aims to identify early warning signs of recessions by analyzing historical U.S. economic
                    and financial data from 1960 to 2024. By combining government economic data with financial market
                    indicators, the analysis seeks to provide a more comprehensive and less biased view of economic
                    conditions.</p>
                <p>Key variables include unemployment rates, GDP growth, inflation, housing prices, the federal funds
                    rate, stock market performance (S&P 500), market volatility (VIX), and the yield curve slope. These
                    indicators have been widely studied and are known to reflect different aspects of the economy.</p>
                <p>The project begins with exploratory data analysis to uncover recurring patterns that appear in the
                    months leading up to past recessions (typically 3–12 months prior). It then applies machine learning
                    techniques—such as logistic regression and time-series modeling—to test whether these patterns
                    consistently signal upcoming downturns.</p>
                <p>The goal is to better understand whether recessions can be anticipated earlier, potentially helping
                    individuals, businesses, and policymakers make more informed decisions.</p>
            </section>

            <div class="content-grid">
                <section id="broader-impacts">
                    <h2>Broader Impacts</h2>
                    <p>Economic downturns can disrupt careers, reduce incomes, and create financial challenges,
                        especially for young adults and financially vulnerable communities. This project aims to improve
                        public awareness of the early warning signs that often appear before recessions, helping
                        individuals and organizations make more informed financial decisions. By identifying consistent
                        patterns in macroeconomic and financial indicators, the research can support better preparation
                        before economic conditions significantly decline.</p>
                    <p>For students and early-career professionals, understanding recession signals can encourage
                        proactive financial behaviors, such as building emergency savings, diversifying income sources,
                        and managing debt responsibly. Small businesses may benefit from earlier strategic adjustments
                        in hiring, inventory, or investment planning. Investors and financial institutions could also
                        use clearer signals to improve risk management and portfolio allocation decisions.</p>
                    <p>From a policy perspective, identifying reliable early indicators may contribute to more timely
                        and targeted economic responses. In addition, this project promotes data literacy by
                        demonstrating how historical economic data and machine learning methods can be applied to
                        real-world challenges. By making complex economic trends more understandable, the research
                        supports stronger financial preparedness and long-term economic resilience across communities.
                    </p>
                </section>

